\begin_layout Abstract
Residential segregation by income severely limits access to opportunity
 for low income households, restricting prospects of upward mobility.
 Land use regulations are one potential determinant of such segregation.
 However, establishing a causal link between such regulation and segregation
 faces two econometric challenges.
 First, regulation is potentially endogenous.
 Second, proper measurement of segregation is difficult.
 With regard to the first challenge, the prior literature relies on instrumental
 variables that may not be valid.
 With regard to the second challenge, the prior literature relies on measures
 that ignore the spatial dimension of segregation.
 This paper uses a new instrumental variable strategy and measures of segregatio
n that account for the spatial distribution of neighborhoods within US metropoli
tan areas.
 The key findings are that stricter overall land use regulation 
\emph on
decreases
\emph default
 segregation within metropolitan areas and that accounting for the spatial
 aspect of segregation matters.
 However, the negative effect appears to be driven by state involvement
 and approval delay; other types of regulation, such as residential density
 restrictions (e.g.
 lot area minimums) and local zoning approval complexity, may 
\emph on
increase
\emph default
 segregation.
\end_layout

