\begin_layout Subsection
Measurement of Segregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My specifications include spatial and aspatial versions of the information
 theory indexes for household income, poverty ratio, and race.
 For each of the spatial information theory indexes, I run specifications
 with measures at 500, 1000, 2000, 4000, and 8000 meter radii.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty et al.
 (2020) find characteristics of blocks only within a mile of a child's block
 help explain a child's future earnings.
 Smaller spatial scales like 500m matter more for those with restricted
 mobility like young children and the elderly.
 Intermediate spatial scales like 2000m may be more important for teenagers.
 Larger distances may matter more for mobile working-age adults.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 My preferred measure is the spatial ordinal information theory index of
 household income segregation.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Massey and Denton (1988) identify five dimensions of segregation: evenness,
 exposure, concentration, centralization, and clustering.
 Reardon and O'Sullivan (2004) condense all five dimensions into two broader
 dimensions: spatial evenness and spatial exposure.
 Spatial evenness reflects how similarly different population groups distribute
 across residential space within a metro area.
 Spatial exposure reflects how prevalent members of one population group
 are in the residential space near a member of another group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
My main specifications use the spatial ordinal information theory index
 from Reardon et al.
 (2006), a weighted average of binary-group segregation values (Reardon
