\end_inset

 (up to a maximum of 1), the more equal are the population shares of categories
 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=2$
\end_inset

 within the MSA or sub-area unit, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Information Theory Index 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H=1-\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{J}\left(\sum_{m=1}^{2}\frac{P_{jm}}{P_{m}}E_{j}\right)}{E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is the number of sub-area units 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in the MSA.
 The Information Theory Index ranges from zero to one.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $H=0$
\end_inset

, knowing the block group a person lives in is no more informative about
 the person's likelihood of belonging to category 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 than is knowing the person's MSA.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $H=1$
\end_inset

, knowing the block group a person lives in fully informs you about the
 category 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to which a person belongs.
 This binary form of the information theory measure (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 has two possible values) provides both my measure of Black-White segregation
 and the components for my primary aspatial measure of income segregation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spatial versions of the information theory index reflect how informative
 knowing a person lives within radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of a Census block group 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is for knowing the category 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to which the person belongs.
 The Spatial Ordinal Information Theory Index 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}$
\end_inset

 accounts for the population composition of nearby sub-area units up to
 some radius distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 500m).
 This is done by creating a Spatial Entropy Diversity Index 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

 for each sub-area unit 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 using proximity-based weights: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{jk}=\begin{cases}
[1-(\frac{d_{jk}}{r})^{2}]^{2} & \textrm{if}\:d_{jk}<r\\
0 & {\textstyle \mathrm{otherwise}}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for every combination of sub-area units 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{jk}$
\end_inset

 is distance in miles between the internal points of sub-area units 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 For each group 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in each sub-area 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, there is a spatially-weighted local population composition (LPC) function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
LPC_{jm}=\frac{\sum_{k\in J}P{}_{km}\times w{}_{jk}}{\sum_{k\in J}(\sum_{n=1}^{2}P{}_{kn})\times w{}_{jk}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that divides the sum of all these weighted nearby-sub-area populations in
 group 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 by the weighted sum of the population overall.
 The Spatial Entropy Diversity Index for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is then: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{E}_{j}=\begin{cases}
\sum_{m=1}^{2}LPC_{jm}\ln(\frac{1}{LPC_{jm}}) & \textrm{if}\:0<LPC_{jm}<1\\
0 & \textrm{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}_{j}$
\end_inset

 into the information theory index gives the Spatial Information Theory
 Index: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{H}=1-\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{J}\left(\frac{P_{j}}{P}\tilde{E}_{j}\right)}{E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The binary form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 has two possible values) provides both my spatial measure of Black-White
 segregation as well as the components for my primary spatial income segregation
 measure, the Spatial Ordinal Information Theory Index.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}=0$
\end_inset

, knowing the block group a person lives in is no more informative about
 the likelihood a neighbor belongs to category 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 than is knowing the person's MSA.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}=1$
\end_inset

, knowing the block group a person lives in fully informs you about the
 category 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to which a neighbor belongs.
 Neighbors include anyone in the same block group and a proximity-weighted
 share of people in other block groups within a specified radius (500m,
 1000m, 2000m, 4000m, or 8000m).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To measure income segregation for my aspatial baseline specification, I
 use the Ordinal Information Theory Index 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{O}$
\end_inset

 (Reardon 2011, Lens and Monkkonen 2016).
 Here, the sub-area units 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are Census block groups, and the sub-population categories 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1,2$
\end_inset

 are the groups above and below an income threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 That is, equation (3) provides 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{t}$
\end_inset

 for a given income threshold.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{O}=\sum_{t=1}^{T}\frac{E_{t}H_{t}}{\sum_{u=1}^{T}E_{u}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is a weighted average of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{t}$
\end_inset

 across all income thresholds 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For my measures, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{t}$
\end_inset

 are binary-group indices of segregation of those above income threshold
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 from those below income threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The two categories 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 are: (1) population above and (2) population below some income threshold
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{t}$
\end_inset

 calculates how closely each block group’s population shares above and below
 income threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 match those of the overall MSA.
 It sums these values of each block group in the MSA weighted by the block
 group’s share of the MSA’s population.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{O}$
\end_inset

 aggregates all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{t}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, weighted by the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{t}$
\end_inset

, which increases the closer 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is to the 50th percentile in the MSA population.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{t}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $E_{u}$
\end_inset

) is the Entropy Diversity Index 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 where the two categories 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 are: (1) population above and (2) population below some income threshold
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To measure income segregation for my spatial specifications, I use the
 Spatial Ordinal Information Theory Index 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}_{O}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{H}_{O}=\sum_{t=1}^{T}\frac{E_{t}\tilde{H}_{t}}{\sum_{u=1}^{T}E_{u}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that is simply the spatial analog of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{O}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

