\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dawkins (2005) examines how local government fragmentation affects residential
 segregation by race across neighborhoods and jurisdictions.
 He uses 1980-2000 US Census of Population and Housing and USGS data on
 number of rivers.
 He expects higher income households will offer higher bids for housing
 in jurisdictions with more local public services if marginal valuation
 of public services rises faster with income than does demand for housing.
 Tiebout choice should thus increase income sorting across jurisdictions,
 and, given Black-White income/wealth gap, increase racial sorting across
 jurisdictions.
 Tiebout choice may also increase racial segregation due to race-correlated
 public services preference heterogeneity and preferences for living near
 people of same race or near people of advantaged race.
 He runs a 2SLS region fixed effects regression for an MSA-level Gini segregatio
n measure on a Herfindahl index of population shares in each jurisdiction
 to measure Tiebout choice instrumented by (1) whether state adopted Dillon’s
 rule restricting local control over incorporation, fiscal policy, and legislati
on; and (2) number of rivers and streams.
 A 10% increase in Tiebout choice increases segregation across neighborhoods
 by no more than 1% and across jurisdictions by 4-7%.
 I adopt the number of rivers measure to instrument for land use regulation.
 If its effect on income segregation just runs through Tiebout choice as
 assumed in this paper, it should be valid for instrumenting land use regulation
, controlling for number of jurisdictions.
 But number of rivers may aid segregation even in absence of land use regulation
 or make historic restrictions on residential location more difficult to
 overcome due to lower social interaction, perhaps resolvable via controls.
 Dillon’s rule, originating in 1873 Iowa, rapidly adopted by other state
 courts and bolstered by the US Supreme Court in 1907 and 1923, can directly
 affect local discretion to set land use regulations but may be associated
 with other state and local policies influencing segregation.
 Richardson, Gough, and Puentes (2003) argues “judicial attitudes and constituti
onal or legislative priorities” largely randomly determine whether a state
 holds to Dillon’s Rule.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

